[2]
Date: Fri 27 Sep 2019
Source: North Carolina Department of Health [edited] https://epi.dph.ncdhhs.gov/cd/legionellosis/outbreak.html


Legionellosis: Investigation of an Outbreak of Legionellosis in Western North Carolina

Current Outbreak
-----------------------
- On 23 Sep 2019, the NC Division of Public Health was notified about an increase in the number of Legionnaire's disease cases in Buncombe and Henderson counties.
- The source of the outbreak is under investigation.
- Many of the cases reported attending the NC Mountain State Fair, held 6-15 Sep 2019 in Fletcher, NC.
- As a precaution, anyone who attended the NC Mountain State Fair and who is experiencing cough, fever or shortness of breath is advised to call their healthcare provider right away and talk to them about Legionnaire's disease. See the provider memo.
- Case finding is ongoing, and additional cases have been reported.
- Case count as of 27 Sep 2019: Buncombe - 34; Granville - 1; Haywood - 5; Henderson - 20; Jackson - 1; Madison - 5; McDowell - 2; Mecklenburg - 2; Mitchell - 1; Rutherford - 1; Transylvania - 3; Watauga - 1; Yancey - 1; and Out of state (SC) - 5. TOTAL - 82. *case counts updated daily.

Case Characteristics: Male - 49 (60%); Female - 33 (40%); Median age in years (range) - 60 (2-90); Hospitalizations - 55; Deaths - 1; Legionnaires' Disease - 78 (95%); Pontiac fever - 4 (5%)

Outbreak Case Definition
-----------------------
Clinical Criteria:
A. Legionnaire's Disease - Pneumonia (clinical or radiologically confirmed) in an individual who attended or worked at the 2019 NC Mountain State Fair, with symptom onset within 2 - 14 days after fair attendance. Or
B. Pontiac Fever - Fever, myalgia, headache, chills, nausea, vomiting or diarrhea within 3 days of attending or working at the 2019 NC Mountain State Fair.

Laboratory Criteria:
Laboratory confirmed _Legionella_:
- By culture - isolation of any _Legionella_ organism from respiratory secretions, lung tissue, pleural fluid, or other normally sterile site; Or
- By detection of _Legionella pneumophila_ serogroup 1 antigen in urine using validated reagents; Or
- By seroconversion: 4-fold or greater rise in specific serum antibody titer to _L. pneumophila_ serogroup 1 using validated reagents on specimens collected 3-6 weeks apart.

Confirmed Case:
Patient meets clinical criteria A or B AND laboratory criteria.
Sources and for more information: CDC: General Information External link (https://www.cdc.gov/legionella/index.html)
CDC: Factsheet (PDF) External link (https://www.cdc.gov/legionella/downloads/fs-legionnaires.pdf)
NC DPH: Legionellosis (https://epi.dph.ncdhhs.gov/cd/diseases/legionellosis.html)
NC DHHS Memo: Increase in Legionnaires' disease cases in western North Carolina (PDF) (https://epi.dph.ncdhhs.gov/cd/legionellosis/NCLegionellosisClincianGuidance_092019.pdf).

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[As of Fri 27 Sep 2019, there are 82 cases of legionellosis associated with the Mountain State Fair that was held in western North Carolina between 6-15 Sep 2019 in Fletcher, a town in Henderson County (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fletcher,_North_Carolina). The fair draws about 190 000 people each year (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/North_Carolina_Mountain_State_Fair).

95% of the cases have Legionnaires' disease, the pneumonic form of the infection, and 5% have Pontiac fever, the non-pneumonic form of the infection. The species of _Legionella_ is not specified; however, the usual pathogen in the US is _Legionella pneumophila_ serogroup 1. The source of the outbreak has not as yet been identified.

The prior news article posted by ProMED-mail reported that all 25 Legionnaires' disease cases reside in counties that immediately surround the location of the fair (Legionellosis - USA (20): (NC) fatal, agricultural fair susp. 20190927.6698517). Currently, the 82 cases come from 13 North Carolina counties. Although most cases reside in western North Carolina counties, some cases reside in counties in the middle of the state, and some cases reside South Carolina. A map showing the location of the North Carolina counties can be found at https://geology.com/county-map/north-carolina.shtml.

Travelers to an event such as a state fair typically disperse to their homes, widely separated from one another and perhaps at a very great distance from the source of infection, before developing symptoms, so that a cluster of cases of Legionnaires' disease in travelers associated with the same source may not be readily appreciated. A travel history is essential and should be actively sought from patients with community-acquired pneumonia, and _Legionella_ testing should be performed for those diagnosed with community-acquired pneumonia who have traveled in the 2 weeks before onset of symptoms. - Mod.ML

HealthMap/ProMED map available at:
North Carolina, United States: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=6700738,235]
